snippet.textDisplay:
There have been some very idiotic diatribes suggesting the #1 tennis player in the world, who donated a million in relief to the Australian government and had a legitimate exemption status, already accepted by the tennis commission, still does not deserve to play because of his un-vaccinated status, pressing the issue of vaccination against a hard mirror of reflection, to suggest everyone should merely play 'follow the leader' on a policy and a vaccine which are fast proving elsewhere in the world to be garnering the necessary scrutiny - finally - to be reconsidered on the growing literature, suggesting the vaccines may not be the panacea and/or gateway to freedom from the pandemic. 

Restricting the unvaccinated from public events, restaurants, concert venues, etc. has not led to an isolation of the variants, but actually an outbreak of staggering proportions of new cases among the fully vaccinated. So, a pandemic of the unvaccinated?!? I think not! And is anyone in the journalistic community even interested in considering whether or not the vaccines may be responsible for boosting the infection rate by weakening those vaccinated natural auto-immune responses to defend against the virus?



Indeed, with over a million people already either dead or maimed by the vaccines in less than a year, is it any wonder concern over vaccination has grown? And Djokovic had an exemption! If we were writing an article about a 'woman's right to choose' over any medical procedure and a government's attempt to merely impose a restriction upon it, I have a sincere feeling the outlook and authorship on this matter would be very different.  As per Novak Djokovic's deportation, tennis is something of a brotherhood. So, what should happen next is an absolute boycott by the rest of the players of the Australian open. 



If one cannot play, the rest should not. In a just, sane world, built upon personal integrity, this would be the recourse of players against an unjust law and the imposition of it by a totalitarian regime. Tennis still has that modicum of integrity to exercise. The Australian government has shown it possesses none!
